# Useful methods

# This function helps to find zero-variance columns for given pandas dataframe
def variance_threshold_selector(data):

    # select a VarianceThreshold model
    selector = VarianceThreshold(0) #Defaults to 0.0, e.g. only remove features with the same value in all samples

    # fit the model
    selector.fit(data)
    features = data.columns.values[selector.get_support(indices = True)]
    
    # format and returnn
    selector = pd.DataFrame(selector.transform(data))
    selector.columns = features
    return selector

# Utility function to report best scores after hypertuning
def report(results, n_top=3):
    for i in range(1, n_top + 1):
        candidates = np.flatnonzero(results['rank_test_score'] == i)
        for candidate in candidates:
            print("Model with rank: {0}".format(i))
            print("Mean validation score: {0:.3f} (std: {1:.3f})".format(
                  results['mean_test_score'][candidate],
                  results['std_test_score'][candidate]))
            print("Parameters: {0}".format(results['params'][candidate]))
            print("")

# Find threshold of -0.70 or +0.70 (Pearson's)
for row in range(pr_cor.shape[0]):
    for col in range(pr_cor.shape[1]):
        # print(row, col)
        if (abs(pr_cor.iloc[row, col]) >= 0.70) and (abs(pr_cor.iloc[row, col]) < 1.0):
            location = (pr_cor.columns[col], pr_cor.index[row])
            print('Found high {} Pearson corr in {}'.format(pr_cor.iloc[row, col], location))

for row in range(sp_cor.shape[0]):
    for col in range(sp_cor.shape[1]):

            location = (sp_cor.columns[col], sp_cor.index[row])
            print('Found high {} Spearman corr in {}'.format(sp_cor.iloc[row, col], location))

# Some words on the success metric: at the moment, we choose the ROC AUC score

# In medicine, ROC analysis has been extensively used in the evaluation of diagnostic tests.
# We're keen on punishing the model in case of many "false negative"
# - as our null hypothesis is "the person is sick", we should avoid situations when sick people are told they're healthy
# This means we must have low Type II error
# Area under the curve score works the best in this situations
In [62]:
params = dict(reduce_dim=[PCA(n_components=5), PCA(n_components=10)],
              clf=[GradientBoostingClassifier(), RandomForestClassifier(n_jobs=-1, oob_score=True)],
              clf__n_estimators=[40, ],

In [68]:
# Conclusions: High ROC-AUC score doesn't guarantee that we'll inform as many sick patients as possible

# This metric got lot of criticism for cases with inbalanced target class (we have such here as well)

# It's better to use the Recall metric from now on
# Recall (R) is defined as the number of true positives (T_p) over the number of true positives 
# plus the number of false negatives (F_n). 
# -- it makes false negatives unwanted - which is good

# Thanks to that we'll recognize sick patients (1) even if sometimes it would cause notifying a
# healthy patient (0) that he might be potentially sick.

# models.append(('GBC', Pipeline([('reduce_dim', PCA(initial_pca)), ('clf', GradientBoostingClassifier())])))
# processor time consuming
models.append(('ADA', Pipeline([('reduce_dim', PCA(initial_pca)), ('clf', AdaBoostClassifier())])))
models.append(('RFC', Pipeline([('reduce_dim', PCA(initial_pca)), ('clf', RandomForestClassifier(n_jobs=-1))])))
models.append(('PAC', Pipeline([('reduce_dim', PCA(initial_pca)), ('clf', PassiveAggressiveClassifier(n_jobs=-1))])))
# models.append(('SGD', Pipeline([('reduce_dim', PCA(initial_pca)), ('clf', SGDClassifier(n_jobs=-1))])))
# not reliable on semi-centered + hot encoded data
models.append(('MLP', Pipeline([('reduce_dim', PCA(initial_pca)), ('clf', MLPClassifier())])))
# models.append(('RBM', Pipeline([('reduce_dim', PCA(initial_pca)), ('clf', BernoulliRBM())])))

# processor time consuming

names = []
scoring = 'recall'  # maybe 'f1', which includes precision
In [73]:
left = len(models)

for name, model in models:
    left -= 1
    print('Testing the {} algorithm, there are {} methods left'.format(name, left))
    kfold = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=n_splits, random_state=42)
    cv_results = model_selection.cross_val_score(model, X, Y, 
                                                 cv=kfold, 
                                                 n_jobs=-1, 
                                                 verbose=0,
                                                 scoring=scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    msg = "%s: %f (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)

# It's possible to build a model which predicts health with 0.965667 recall and 0.973480 F-1 score

# It's not obvious which score function to choose, although a harmonic sum of precision and recall should be enough
